Front:
Given:
L = [[3, 9], [4, 16], [5, 25]]
What does the following pseudocode produce?

squares = []
foreach pair in L {
squares = squares ++ [last(pair)]
}
A) [3, 4, 5]
B) [9, 16, 25]
C) [[3, 9], [4, 16], [5, 25]]
D) [last(L)]

What will be the output of this pseudocode?

L = [[1, 2, 7], [4, 5, 6]]
result = []
foreach x in L {
result = result ++ [first(rest(x))]
}
A) [2, 5]
B) [1, 4]
C) [3, 6]
D) [rest(L)]

What is the result of the following code?

A = [1, 5, 5, 7, 9]
B = [2, 5, 6, 7, 10]
common = []

foreach x in A {
foreach y in B {
if x == y {
common = common ++ [x]
}
}
}
A) [3, 7]
B) [1, 3, 5]
C) [2, 6]
D) []

Suppose a function `eliminate(L1, L2)` removes elements of L1 that are also in L2.
If L1 = [1, 2, 6, 4], and L2 = [2, 4], what will eliminate(L1, L2) return?
A) [1, 3]
B) [2, 4]
C) [1, 2, 3, 4]
D) []

How many numbers between 1 and 50 (inclusive) are both in:
- every 5rd element starting from 1
- every 4th element starting from 2

Enter the count.
A) 4
B) 3
C) 2
D) 1
